addr="lankham-2016-linear"
title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Theorem 8.2.3</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A=(a_{ij})\in \mathbb {F}^{n\times  n}]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix with entries in the <fr:link
type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>. Then the following all holds:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>Determinant of zero matrix is zero: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (0_{n\times  n})=0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Determinant of identity matrix is one: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det {I}=1]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{1},…,a_{n}]]></fr:tex> be the column vectors of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A=(a_{1}|…|a_{n}).]]></fr:tex> Then the determinant is a linear function of the columns <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (a_{1}|…|ca_{i}|…|a_{n})=c\det (a_{1}|…|a_{i}|…|a_{n})]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c\in \mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (a_{1}|…|a_{i}+b_{i}|…|a_{n})=\det (a_{1}|…|a_{i}|…|a_{n})+\det (a_{1}|…|b_{i}|…|a_{n})]]></fr:tex> for any column vector <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b_{i}\in \mathbb {F}^{n}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>The determinant is an antisymmetric function of the columns of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>: for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi \in  S_{n}]]></fr:tex>, letting <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{1},…,a_{n}]]></fr:tex> be the column vectors of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi (a_{\pi (1)}|…|a_{\pi (n)})=\mathop {\textrm {sgn}}\nolimits (\pi )\det (A)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has two identical columns, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (A)=0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> has a column of zeroes, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (A)=0]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (A^{\mathsf {T}})=\det (A)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B\in \mathbb {F}^{n\times  n}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (AB)=\det (A)\det (B)]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a triangular matrix, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\det (A)=\prod ^{n}_{i=1}a_{i,i}]]></fr:tex> is just the product of the diagonal entries.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
