title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Recall <fr:link
type="local"
href="vectsp-001Y.xml"
addr="vectsp-001Y"
title="Differentiation is a linear operator on space of polynomials">Differentiation is a linear operator on space of polynomials</fr:link>. So for a <fr:link
type="local"
href="field-0001.xml"
addr="field-0001"
title="Field">Field</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>, the vector space of polynomials <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}[z]]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex> in unknown <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {d} /\mathrm {d} z]]></fr:tex> be a linear operator on it. Can we compute the determinant of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {d} /\mathrm {d} z]]></fr:tex>? That is, can we make sense of
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\det \left (\frac {\mathrm {d}}{\mathrm {d} z}\right )]]></fr:tex>
in some way? More generally, if we consider any linear differential operator, can we compute its determinant?</fr:p><fr:p>Such expressions appear in quantum mechanics and quantum field theory.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
